[Since certification for international trade, as described in the recommendations above, is partly based upon serological tests, it is appropriate to present here the passage "Laboratory diagnosis" from the chapter "diagnosis" in OIE's new technical factsheet on SBV.

"1. Samples:
a. From live animals for the detection of acute infection:
- EDTA blood;
- Serum (at least 2 ml, transported cooled).
b. From stillborns and malformed calves, lambs and kids:
- From necropsy: tissue samples of brain (cerebrum and cerebellum), additional samples: central nervous system, spleen and blood
- From live newborn: blood, (preferably pre-colostral) serum, and meconium (Samples should be transported cooled or frozen).
- Placenta and amniotic fluids.
2. Procedures:
a. Identification of the agent
- Real-time RT-PCR
- Cell culture isolation of the virus
b. Serological tests on serum samples
- Indirect immunofluorescence
- Neutralization test
- ELISA to be developed."

OIE is commendable for convening the expert ad-hoc group and the issuance of the recommendations and the technical factsheet, despite the fact that (the emerging) SBV is not included (yet?) in OIE's list of notifiable diseases. Subscribers may be reminded that Akabane virus, to which reference is made in the documents above, is also not an OIE listed disease.

Several countries have already applied restrictions on the import of animals, particularly genetic material from ruminants from the SBV affected countries or from Europe. The recommendations will, hopefully, provide assistance in their risk assessment. - Mod.AS

